Gastroschisis vs Omphalocele — distinct entities: Gastroschisis: defect right of umbilicus (paraumbilical), NO covering membrane, bowel exposed (often inflamed/thickened from amniotic fluid exposure), umbilical cord normal position, LOW association with other anomalies (5-10%) but high bowel atresia; Omphalocele: midline defect at umbilical cord, COVERED by amnion + peritoneum membrane (may rupture), liver + bowel inside sac, HIGH association with chromosomal (trisomy 13, 18, 21) + cardiac anomalies (30-50%), Beckwith-Wiedemann, pentalogy of Cantrell; Management of gastroschisis:

(1) Immediate: cover exposed bowel with sterile saline-soaked gauze + cling wrap or bowel bag; NPO, NG decompression, IV fluid (large losses), IV antibiotic, thermoregulation (high losses → hypothermia);

(2) Operative — primary closure if abdominal cavity can accommodate (no compartment syndrome); OR staged with silo (preformed silastic silo or surgical silo) → daily reduction over 5-10 days → delayed closure;

(3) Post-op: TPN until bowel function returns (often weeks), gradual enteral feeds;

(4) Complications: short gut syndrome, motility disorders, atresia (concurrent), feeding intolerance;

(5) Omphalocele management: similar staged approach but slower (large defects); 'paint + wait' (silver sulfadiazine, escharification) for giant defects; sac itself protects; associated anomaly workup essential (echo, karyotype, etc.);

(6) Long-term: most do well; nutritional + developmental follow-up
————————————————
Abdominal wall defects — two main: Gastroschisis vs Omphalocele. Differentiation critical for management + prognosis. Gastroschisis: right paraumbilical, no sac, inflamed bowel, fewer associations, primary or staged silo closure. Omphalocele: midline, intact sac, liver + bowel, MANY associated anomalies (cardiac 30-50%, chromosomal — trisomies, Beckwith-Wiedemann, Cantrell pentalogy), echo + karyotype workup essential. Both need NG decompression, IV fluid, thermoregulation, antibiotic, and surgical management (primary or staged silo). Outcomes generally good with modern care; long-term issues: feeding, growth, motility, short gut if extensive bowel resection.

