Perioperative medication management — specific decisions:

(1) Antihypertensives:
  • ACE-I / ARB: HOLD on day of surgery — intraoperative hypotension; resume post-op when hemodynamically stable
  • Beta-blocker: CONTINUE if chronic; DO NOT initiate new (POISE — increased death + stroke)
  • Calcium channel blocker: continue
  • Diuretic: hold day of surgery typically (volume + electrolyte)
  • Clonidine (α2-agonist): continue (withdrawal rebound HTN);

(2) Antidiabetic:
  • Metformin: usually OK day before; hold day of surgery for major (lactic acidosis risk if CKD);
  • Sulfonylureas: hold day of surgery (hypoglycemia)
  • SGLT2 inhibitor (canagliflozin, empagliflozin, dapagliflozin): HOLD 3-4 days pre-op (DKA risk — euglycemic DKA can occur with normal glucose; FDA warning)
  • GLP-1 (semaglutide, liraglutide, tirzepatide): HOLD 1 week pre-op for daily, 2 weeks for weekly (delayed gastric emptying → aspiration risk during anesthesia — ASA + ASRA guidance 2023)
  • DPP-4 inhibitor (sitagliptin): usually continue
  • Insulin: long-acting reduced dose night before + day of, short-acting hold day of, sliding scale + correction;

(3) Anticoagulant + antiplatelet: see prior question on perioperative anticoagulation;

(4) Statin: CONTINUE — perioperative cardiovascular protection;

(5) Hormonal:
