ATLS (Advanced Trauma Life Support) — systematic approach:

(1) Pre-arrival: communication with EMS, team activation, prepare equipment, blood products, OR notification;

(2) Primary survey ABCDE — identify + treat life-threats simultaneously:
  • A — Airway with cervical spine protection: assess patency, talking = patent; obstructed → jaw thrust, suction, oral/nasal airway, supraglottic, intubation (rapid sequence with C-spine inline immobilization), surgical airway last resort;
  • B — Breathing: inspect, palpate, percuss, auscultate; identify life-threats: tension pneumothorax (needle/finger decompression — 5th ICS anterior axillary), open pneumothorax (3-sided occlusive dressing), massive hemothorax (chest tube > 1.5L initial OR > 200 mL/hr × 4h → OR), flail chest (positive pressure ventilation if respiratory failure);
  • C — Circulation + hemorrhage control: assess pulse, capillary refill, mental status, BP; identify hemorrhage sources: external (direct pressure, tourniquet, hemostatic gauze), thoracic (chest tube), abdominal (FAST), pelvic (binder + angio + REBOA), retroperitoneal, long bone fractures (splinting + ortho); 2 large-bore IV (16-18g) or IO; type & cross; balanced resuscitation (1:1:1 PRC:FFP:Plt early in massive bleed per PROPPR); permissive hypotension (no TBI); TXA early (CRASH-2 + CRASH-3); MTP activation; calcium (citrate binding)
  • D — Disability: GCS (E4V5M6 = 15), pupil (size + reactivity), gross motor; head trauma signs
  • E — Exposure + environmental: completely undress, log roll, look for occult injuries (back, axilla, perineum); rewarm aggressively (hypothermia worsens coagulopathy + acidosis = lethal triad); avoid cold IV fluid;

(3) Adjuncts to primary survey: FAST exam (or eFAST including lung), CXR, pelvis XR, ECG, ABG, lactate, type + cross, urinary catheter (if no urethral injury — blood at meatus, high-riding prostate), NG/OG;

(4) Reassess + identify undiagnosed life threats;

(5) Secondary survey — head-to-toe systematic exam + AMPLE history (Allergies, Medications, Past, Last meal, Events); only after primary stabilized; identify all injuries — log roll + back exam, head + maxillofacial, neck + C-spine, chest, abdomen + pelvis, perineum + rectal, musculoskeletal, neurological detailed;

(6) Definitive care + transfer — to appropriate trauma center if needed; do NOT delay definitive care for prolonged workup; OR + IR + ICU coordination;

(7) Tertiary survey — within 24h, identifies missed injuries (5-10% miss rate without tertiary);

(8) Special populations:
  • Pediatric: weight-based dosing, anatomical differences, vital sign norms differ, NAT consideration
  • Geriatric: under-triage common due to compensated initial vitals; lower threshold for trauma center
  • Pregnant: maternal first (best for fetus); left lateral tilt (avoid IVC compression > 20 weeks); fetal monitoring; Rh status (Rhogam)
  • Anticoagulated: reversal (PCC, TXA, FFP); reverse first then evaluate;

(9) Damage control resuscitation (DCR) + damage control surgery (DCS) principles when severely injured;

(10) Communication + handoff structured (SBAR); patient + family disclosure
